061":"1061","1093":"1093","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1117":"1117","1128":"1128","1025":"1025","Abt 1055":"circa 1055","1034":"1034","about 1049":"circa 1049","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Rhuddlan, Flint, Wales":"Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales","St Euphamie, Sardinia, Italy":"Sardinia, Sardegna, Italië","Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","England":"England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Calabria, Italy":"Calabria, Italië","Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales":"Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales"},"en":{"Abt 1055–1121":"about 1055–1121","1055–1121":"1055–1121","1060–Female":"1060–Deceased","1061–1117":"1061–1117","1075–1128":"1075–1128","1093–Female":"1093–Deceased","1025–Male":"1025–Deceased","1034–1082":"1034–1082","1121":"1121","1055":"1055","12 December 1082":"12 December 1082","1087":"1087","1075":"1075","1085":"1085","1061":"1061","1093":"1093","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1117":"1117","1128":"1128","1025":"1025","Abt 1055":"about 1055","1034":"1034","about 1049":"about 1049","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Rhuddlan, Flint, Wales":"Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales","St Euphamie, Sardinia, Italy":"Sardinia, Sardinia, Italy","Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Caen, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","England":"England","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Calabria, Italy":"Calabria, Italy","Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales":"Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Roelent was born about 1055, in Caen, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France, his father, Honfroi le Goz, was 32 and his mother, Adeliza de Grandmesnil, was 23. He married Cecily de Bassett in 1085, in Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1121, at the age of 67."},"et":{"Abt 1055–1121":"umbes 1055–1121","1055–1121":"1055–1121","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1061–1117":"1061–1117","1075–1128":"1075–1128","1093–Female":"1093–Surnud","1025–Male":"1025–Surnud","1034–1082":"1034–1082","1121":"1121","1055":"1055","12 December 1082":"12. detsember 1082","1087":"1087","1075":"1075","1085":"1085","1061":"1061","1093":"1093","1082":"1082","1060":"1060","1117":"1117","1128":"1128","1025":"1025","Abt 1055":"umbes 1055","1034":"1034","about 1049":"